  "prompt": "If light does not have mass, then how can it bend due to gravity? How can light have momentum if mass is 0?",
  "response": "Great question! This touches on some fascinating aspects of modern physics. Let me break down the explanation:\n\n1. Light and Gravity (Bending)\n- According to Einstein's General Relativity, gravity isn't just a force, but a curvature of spacetime\n- Massive objects like stars and black holes warp the fabric of spacetime\n- Light follows the curvature of spacetime, which appears as \"bending\"\n- This isn't mass-based attraction, but a consequence of spacetime geometry\n\n2. Light's Momentum\n- Momentum is calculated by p = mv (mass \u00d7 velocity)\n- For light, we use the quantum/relativistic equation: p = h/\u03bb\n- h is Planck's constant, \u03bb is wavelength\n- Light has momentum due to its energy, not traditional mass\n- E = mc\u00b2 can be rearranged to show energy-momentum relationship\n\n3. Photon Properties\n- Photons are massless particles\n- They always travel at light speed\n- Carry energy and momentum through wave-particle duality\n- Momentum determined by frequency/wavelength, not mass\n\nThese concepts demonstrate how classical physics breaks down at quantum and relativistic scales, requiring more sophisticated mathematical models to explain phenomena.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these points?",
